Exercises

Context

This cartoon by Alison Bechdel inspired the âBechdel testâ (image source):

A movie passes the test if it meets the following criteria:

  • there are at least 2 women-identifying characters;
  • these characters talk to each other at least 1 time; and
  • they talk about something other than a male-identifying character

Weâll work with the bechdel data within the fivethirtyeight package. You can enter ?bechdel in the Console to view the codebook.

Exercise 4: How much money did it make?

The intgross_mil variable records each movieâs total international gross, in millions of dollars (and adjusted to 2013).

  1. Almost all movies grossed under $1,000,000,000 with the majority grossing under $500,000,000. The distribution is right-skewed with an outlier â a movie that grossed much higher than the others (more than $3,000,000,000).
# A histogram, density plot, boxplot, or other would work. You only need one!
ggplot(bechdel, aes(x = intgross_mil)) +
    geom_histogram()
  1. The mean is pulled up by the outliers, whereas the median isnât influenced by these outliers (itâs calculated using only the middle numbers). In this case, the mean provides a misleading calculation of whatâs âtypicalâ, thus the median is more appropriate here.
bechdel %>% 
    summarize(
        mean(intgross_mil, na.rm = TRUE),
        median(intgross_mil, na.rm = TRUE)
    )
## # A tibble: 1 Ã 2
##   `mean(intgross_mil, na.rm = TRUE)` `median(intgross_mil, na.rm = TRUE)`
##                                <dbl>                                <dbl>
## 1                               198.                                 96.2
  1. Thereâs more variability in how much money movies make at the box office than in how much money is spent making movies.

Exercise 5: Explaining intgross_mil

Next, letâs try to explain some of the variability in how much money films gross. To this end, weâll focus on modeling intgross_mil by budget_mil. That is, to what extent is the money a film makes related to its budget?

  1. Response = intgross_mil. Predictor = budget_mil

ggplot(bechdel, aes(y = intgross_mil, x = budget_mil)) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
  1. Thereâs a positive trend in the relationship between budget and gross: movies that cost more money to make tend to make more at the box office. However, thereâs quite a bit of deviation from the trend. For example, there are several movies that make much more than expected.

Exercise 6: Modeling intgross_mil

movie_model <- lm(intgross_mil ~ budget_mil, data = bechdel)
coef(summary(movie_model))
##              Estimate Std. Error   t value      Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept) 27.138951 7.69379045  3.527384  4.303247e-04
## budget_mil   3.063147 0.09829586 31.162528 1.574335e-170

  1. E[intgross_mil | budget_mil] = 27.138951 + 3.063147 budget_mil (Answers may vary due to rounding)

  2. For every extra 1 million dollars spent on making the movie, the expected gross increases by roughly $3.06 million.

  3. It doesnât make sense to interpret the intercept in this model. This would be the expected gross of a movie that had a $0 budget. No such movies exist in this data set.
